  "title": "Liberalism vs Conservatism: Core Political Philosophies",
  "content": "<h2>Learning Objectives</h2><p>Understand origins, definitions, differences, and Australian examples of Liberalism vs Conservatism.</p><h2>Historical Origins</h2><h3>Liberalism</h3><p>Emerged in <strong>Enlightenment (17th-18th centuries)</strong> with thinkers like <strong>John Locke</strong> (individual rights, limited government). Evolved through American/French Revolutions, emphasizing liberty, equality, progress. 19th-century classical liberalism focused on free markets (Adam Smith); modern social liberalism adds welfare (John Stuart Mill, FDR's New Deal).</p><h3>Conservatism</h3><p>Rooted in reaction to French Revolution (<strong>Edmund Burke</strong> critiqued radical change). Emphasizes tradition, hierarchy, stability. Evolved with 19th-century monarchism, 20th-century anti-communism (Reagan/Thatcher neoliberalism).</p><h2>Definitions</h2><h3>Liberalism</h3><p>Ideology prioritizing individual freedoms, equality, rational progress. Supports government intervention for social justice, civil rights.</p><h3>Conservatism</h3><p>Ideology valuing tradition, order, moral authority. Prefers gradual change, limited government in personal/economic spheres.</p><h2>Comparison Table (Expanded)</h2><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Liberalism</th><th>Conservatism</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Core Values</td><td>Liberty, equality, progress, human rights.</td><td>Tradition, order, hierarchy, duty.</td></tr><tr><td>Government Role</td><td>Active intervention (welfare, regulations).</td><td>Limited (defense, law; markets handle rest).</td></tr><tr><td>Economy</td><td>Mixed: free markets with redistribution (taxes, aid).</td><td>Free markets, low taxes, deregulation.</td></tr><tr><td>Social Issues</td><td>Progressive: supports LGBTQ+ rights, abortion, diversity.</td><td>Traditional: family values, religion, cultural norms.</td></tr><tr><td>Change</td><td>Embraces reform, innovation.</td><td>Resists rapid change; preserves status quo.</td></tr><tr><td>Foreign Policy</td><td>Internationalism, cooperation (UN, alliances).</td><td>Nationalism, strong defense.</td></tr><tr><td>Environment</td><td>Regulations, climate action.</td><td>Market solutions, balanced with economy.</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Global Examples</h2><ul><li><strong>US:</strong> Liberals (Democrats) - social programs; Conservatives (Republicans) - tax cuts.</li><li><strong>UK:</strong> Liberals (Lib Dems) - civil liberties; Conservatives (Tories) - Brexit nationalism.</li></ul><h2>Australian Example</h2><h3>Liberalism</h3><p>Australian Labor Party (ALP) embodies social liberalism: Medicare, NDIS, climate targets (Albanese govt 2022+). Focuses on equality, workers' rights.</p><h3>Conservatism</h3><p>Liberal Party (with Nationals) - economic conservatism: tax cuts, deregulation (Morrison era). Emphasizes borders, tradition (Dutton opposition).</p><h2>Evolution & Criticisms</h2><h3>Evolution</h3><p>Liberalism shifted left (welfare); Conservatism adopted market liberalism.</p><h3>Criticisms</h3><p>Liberalism seen as elitist/chaotic; Conservatism as resistant to progress.</p><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><ul><li><strong>Liberalism:</strong> Freedom through reform.</li><li><strong>Conservatism:</strong> Stability through tradition.</li></ul>",
